      <hedline>
        <hl1>An Israeli Constitution</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Marc E Hofstadter letter supports Israeli Prime Min Ehud Barak's attempt to create constitution</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It's interesting that some in Israel portray Prime Minister Ehud Barak's attempt to create a constitution  as an effort that polarizes society and favors the secular over the religious (news article, Sept. 17). As things stand now, religious people don't believe in riding buses on the Sabbath, so no one can ride a bus on the Sabbath.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It's interesting that some in Israel portray Prime Minister Ehud Barak's attempt to create a constitution  as an effort that polarizes society and favors the secular over the religious (news article, Sept. 17). As things stand now, religious people don't believe in riding buses on the Sabbath, so no one can ride a bus on the Sabbath.</p>
        <p>Most rabbis don't recognize Reform or Conservative conversions, so the whole country is forced to accept their view. The Orthodox minority doesn't support equality between men and women, so equality is denied for all.</p>
        <p>An equitable constitution would provide rights for all, including the religious, while ensuring that no minority convictions are imposed on the whole country. Mr. Barak's cause seems to me high-minded and just.</p>
        <p>MARC E. HOFSTADTER  Oakland, Calif., Sept. 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
